http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/nottinghamshire/6647431.stm	BBC NEWS | England | Nottinghamshire | Boy's fight to cure rare disease Skip to bbc.co.uk navigation Your news when you want it Friday, 11 May 2007, 15:18 GMT 16:18 UK E-mail this to a friend Boy's fight to cure rare disease Jack only has half the movement in his right arm A 12-year-old boy from Nottinghamshire is fighting to find a cure for a rare bone disease. Jack Beaumont, from Sutton-in-Ashfield, is believed to be one of just 300 people in the world who have been diagnosed with melorheostosis. The disease, which causes excess bone growth, has left Jack with half the normal movement in his right arm. He was meeting experts at a national conference on melorheostosis in Oxford on Friday. Jack and fellow sufferers shared their stories at the UK Melorheostosis Conference. "I'm hoping for some answers and I'm looking forward to meeting some other people who've got the same disease as me," he said. His mother, Nicola Beaumont, added: "He just shrugs it off because he's so laid back, nothing affects him in that respect but I think as he gets older, he's going to find more restrictions." E-mail this to a friend VIDEO AND AUDIO NEWS Jack Beaumont talks about his hopes for a cure Sport, travel, leisure and more from the BBC website for Nottingham The BBC is not responsible for the content of external internet sites Man, 80, attacked by city mugger Disabled resident choked on onion Girls hand out Madeleine posters MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW A pygmy conference in the rainforest Underground search for 'God particle' Google searches web's dark side Zimbabwe to chair major UN body Hero's return for Knox-Johnston Most popular now, in detail New plea on Madeleine's birthday Thatcher unveils Falklands arch Woman destroyed her unborn baby Eurovision's other 'Terry Wogans' Coalition troops missing in Iraq Most popular now, in detail Estonia's statue row: Hand of Moscow or sure vote-winner? Pygmies hold a conference in Con