http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/rss/-/1/hi/northern_ireland/6645479.stm	BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | Baby unit 'to re-open next week' Skip to bbc.co.uk navigation Your news when you want it Friday, 11 May 2007, 17:42 GMT 18:42 UK E-mail this to a friend Baby unit 'to re-open next week' The neonatal unit treats the sickest babies in Northern Ireland A consultant at the neonatal unit in Belfast where three premature babies picked up an infection said it hopes to resume admissions next week. The Royal Maternity Hospital closed the unit temporarily to new admissions after the babies became seriously ill. The ward has now been chemically decontaminated. Health Minister Michael McGimpsey said eliminating infections in hospitals was a priority. Dr Stanley Craig said the babies were responding well to antibiotics. "Any infection when you're particularly compromised, as a pre-term baby is, is potentially life-threatening," he said. "These babies are responding to the antibiotics that they're on, which is good news for the babies themselves, their parents and the staff involved in their care. The hospital hopes to re-open the unit next week "Being born premature does leave you very vulnerable to infection and it can be a problem, but we're seeing encouraging signs." The babies, who picked up a multi-resistant enterobacter infection, have been isolated and are being closely monitored by specially trained nurses. The health minister said the situation was not acceptable and pointed out there had been much investment in the area of patient safety. "It is one of the issues that we look at ...and it's one of the areas I take very, very seriously," said Mr McGimpsey. "Obviously when people go to hospital they expect not to pick up infection, when they're there. There is an incidence of infections in hospitals and we look to eliminate that because whatever the incidence is, it is ... too high." Iris Robinson of the DUP said she was concerned about the impact on other hospitals. "What I am particularly concerned about is how the other hospitals across the province are going to deal with demand while the Royal's neonatal unit is out of operation," she said. "Usually the most unwell babies from all around Northern Ireland would be transferred to the specialist unit in Belfast. "Obviously this will not be the case for the immediate future, and these cases will have to be managed in their local units." E-mail this to a friend VIDEO AND AUDIO NEWS Dot Kirby reports on the units closure Royal Hospitals maternity unit The BBC is not responsible for the content of external internet sites TOP NORTHERN IRELAND STORIES Brown 'has no extra cash' for NI Two die in separate road crashes Couple are rescued from flat fire MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW A pygmy conference in the rainforest Underground search for 'God particle' Google searches web's dark side Zimbabwe to chair major UN body Hero's return for Knox-Johnston Most popular now, in detail New plea on Madeleine's birthday Thatcher unveils Falklands arch Woman destroyed her unborn baby Eurovision's other 'Terry Wogans' Coalition troops missing in Iraq Most popular now, in detail Estonia's statue row: Hand of Moscow or sure vote-winner? Pygmies hold a conference in Congo's tropical rainforest We meet Eurovision commentators from around the continent Back to top ^^ Privacy and cookies policy
http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/rss/-/1/hi/northern_ireland/6645479.stm	BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | Baby unit 'to re-open next week' Skip to bbc.co.uk navigation Your news when you want it Friday, 11 May 2007, 17:42 GMT 18:42 UK E-mail this to a friend Baby unit 'to re-open next week' The neonatal unit treats the sickest babies in Northern Ireland A consultant at the neonatal unit in Belfast where three premature babies picked up an infection said it hopes to resume admissions next week. The Royal Maternity Hospital closed the unit temporarily to new admissions after the babies became seriously ill. The ward has now been chemically decontaminated. Health Minister Michael McGimpsey said eliminating infections in hospitals was a priority. Dr Stanley Craig said the babies were responding well to antibiotics. "Any infection when you're particularly compromised, as a pre-term baby is, is potentially life-threatening," he said. "These babies are responding to the antibiotics that they're on, which is good news for the babies themselves, their parents and the staff involved in their care. The hospital hopes to re-open the unit next week "Being born premature does leave you very vulnerable to infection and it can be a problem, but we're seeing encouraging signs." The babies, who picked up a multi-resistant enterobacter infection, have been isolated and are being closely monitored by specially trained nurses. The health minister said the situation was not acceptable and pointed out there had been much investment in the area of patient safety. "It is one of the issues that we look at ...and it's one of the areas I take very, very seriously," said Mr McGimpsey. "Obviously when people go to hospital they expect not to pick up infection, when they're there. There is an incidence of infections in hospitals and we look to eliminate that because whatever the incidence is, it is ... too high." Iris Robinson of the DUP said she was concerned about the impact on other hospitals. "What I am particularly concerned about is how the other hospitals across the province are going to deal with demand while the Royal's neonatal unit is out of operation," she said. "Usually the most unwell babies from all around Northern Ireland would be transferred to the specialist unit in Belfast. "Obviously this will not be the case for the immediate future, and these cases will have to be managed in their local units." E-mail this to a friend VIDEO AND AUDIO NEWS Dot Kirby reports on the units closure Royal Hospitals maternity unit The BBC is not responsible for the content of external internet sites TOP NORTHERN IRELAND STORIES Brown 'has no extra cash' for NI Two die in separate road crashes Couple are rescued from flat fire MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW A pygmy conference in the rainforest Underground search for 'God particle' Google searches web's dark side Zimbabwe to chair major UN body Hero's return for Knox-Johnston Most popular now, in detail New plea on Madeleine's birthday Thatcher unveils Falklands arch Woman destroyed her unborn baby Eurovision's other 'Terry Wogans' Coalition troops missing in Iraq Most popular now, in detail Estonia's statue row: Hand of Moscow or sure vote-winner? Pygmies hold a conference in Congo's tropical rainforest We meet Eurovision commentators from around the continent Back to top ^^ Privacy and cookies policy
http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/6644293.stm	BBC NEWS | Health | Call for mental heath care push Skip to bbc.co.uk navigation Your news when you want it Friday, 11 May 2007, 07:27 GMT 08:27 UK E-mail this to a friend Call for mental heath care push Most mental health treatment takes place out of hospitals Mental health services must renew their efforts to improve community care, the mental health tsar says. Professor Louis Appleby has called on NHS trusts to look at new ways of working to help people rebuild lives. He said they should look to work more closely with employment and housing agencies and cut waiting lists for talking therapies in England. Campaigners said there was a lot of work to do to ensure services were good enough for patients. In the last eight years, there has been a big push to move care out of hospitals and into the community. With units and day centres closing and community services cut, the more seriously ill are still being neglected and put at risk Marjorie Wallace, of Sane There are now more than 700 community teams, including nurses, doctors and social workers, providing a range of crisis help and early intervention. However, the Healthcare Commission last year criticised services, pointing to gaps in out-of-hours care, talking therapies and access to information. Nearly half of services were rated as fair or weak. Professor Appleby said the report was about the next phase of reform of mental health care. He told BBC News: "We've had several years of strengthening what community services do, and the report is about breaking down the barriers in the next stage of reforms. "I'm talking about barriers that get in the way of better patients' experience of care "At the moment, for example, there is a barrier between what health services traditionally do, which is clinical care, improving people's illnesses, abolishing their symptoms. "But what patients often tell us they want is help with quality of life. They want opportunities for training, for jobs, and for decent housing, and we have to take on that responsibility." His report called on the 60 mental heath trusts to consult with their local populations about what they needed. The report said mental health trusts should look at ways they could link up with agencies responsible for housing and employment. It also called for community teams to get involved in giving people more advice on how to reduce alcohol and drug use and look after their physical health. He also called for a renewed effort to reduce waiting lists for talking therapies such as cognitive behavioural therapy, which sometimes has waits of over 12 months. The NHS is currently rolling out a programme of providing people with access to computerised CBT and the government has set up 10 pilots to explore ways of speeding up access to talking therapies. Marjorie Wallace, chief executive of the mental health charity Sane, said extra investment was needed. "We are all too aware that with units and day centres closing and community services cut, the more seriously ill are still being neglected and put at risk. "The government goes forward with its policy of reform and choice, but there are thousands who have no choice of where to go in crisis and little chance of rehabilitation or safe, consistent care, both in or out of hospital." E-mail this to a friend Firms urged to help mentally ill Mental health wards 'unpleasant' Mental health services 'failing' Young 'failed' on mental health Fear over health of mentally ill 'My company helped me recover' 'The services were just not there' 'I'm so glad I didn't kill myself' 'I have washed my hands of NHS' 'I learned to live with voices' Kicking depression into touch The BBC is not responsible for the content of external internet sites Healthcare top priority for Brown 'Half' unaware of smoke ban date Surgeons warn on salon treatments MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW A pygmy conference in the rainforest Underground search for 'God particle' Google searches web